{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17496353","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17496353"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T08:45:22+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T08:45:22+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1343"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1343","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1343"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.1,0.42,0.01,0.34,0.13]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1343"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"49664"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1343","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1343"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1343"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"34943"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"141"},{"type":"tags","id":"4962"},{"type":"tags","id":"4977"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11626"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1915"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1997"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12818"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17602"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42289"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"49664","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/49664"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA previously well 68-year-old man presents with two months of back pain and bilateral lower leg weakness. A detailed history does not provide any other information apart from a loss of libido over the last few years. On examination, there is palpable tenderness over the spinous process in the lumbar region. Strength is 4/5 bilaterally and neurological examination is otherwise unremarkable. It is noted that the man has enlarged breast tissue. There are no visual field defects.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInitial laboratory tests including a complete blood examination, electrolytes, urea, creatinine and calcium reveal no abnormalities. A lumbar spine X ray is performed (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely underlying cause of his current problem?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Primary hyperparathyroidism","Hypogonadism","Graves disease","Long-term corticosteroid use","Multiple myeloma"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis lateral radiograph shows crush fractures of the third and fourth lumbar vertebrae. Pathological fractures are bone fractures caused by diseases that lead to weakness in bone structures. The most common underlying process is osteoporosis, and in men up to 50% of patients with osteoporosis have an underlying cause, known as secondary osteoporosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHypogonadism\u003C/strong\u003E is the correct answer, as suggested by the symptom of loss of libido and the examination finding of gynaecomastia. Low androgen levels reduce osteoblast proliferation and result in diminished inhibitory effect on osteoclasts.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThere is no explicit mention of \u003Cstrong\u003Elong-term corticosteroid use\u003C/strong\u003E in the stem, nor is there any suggestion from a past medical history perspective (e.g. history of systemic lupus erythematosus, solid organ transplantation etc.) that the patient may have had long-term corticosteroid exposure. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn \u003Cstrong\u003Eprimary hyperparathyroidism\u003C/strong\u003E, increased parathyroid hormone secretion would result in hypercalcaemia. The serum calcium in the stem is normal, hence, making this answer less likely. There are also no biochemical abnormalities in the stem to suggest the alternative answers of \u003Cstrong\u003EGraves\u0027 disease\u003C/strong\u003E or \u003Cstrong\u003Emultiple myeloma\u003C/strong\u003E. \u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Hypogonadism is a secondary cause of osteoporosis in older men."],"references":["Misiorowski W. Osteoporosis in men. Prz Menopauzalny. 2017 Jun;16(2):70-73. doi: 10.5114/pm.2017.68596. Epub 2017 Jun 30."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"34943"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1343"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"19900"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"19900","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/19900"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/91392617-e20e-4deb-90ec-4b992fdb187a.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/91392617-e20e-4deb-90ec-4b992fdb187a.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":198,"height":431}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"34943","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/34943"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-08-02T22:23:04+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-08-02T22:23:48+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1343"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"49664"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"4","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf6c","name":"Endocrinology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud